³ Scia insum—Now Skye. See i. 33 (p. 62) supra. The chief patron saints of this island were St. Columba and St. Maelrubha: the for- mer having the north-eastern, and the latter the south-eastern portion. Killashig, or As- kimilruby, with Kilmaree in Strath, and Kil- molruy in Bmckadale, were commemorative of St. Maelrubha, whose principal church oprer- crossan, now Applecross, is within view on the main land to the north-east. The portion of the island peculiar to St. Columba is that part

of Trotternish bounded by a line drawn from Portree to the head of Loch Snizort. At tho north-western extremity of this district, in the parish of Kilmuin about two and a half miles north of Uig Bay, is the alluvial bed of a lake formerly known as Loch Colnmkille, which was drained some thirty years ago by Lord Maedo- nald, the proprietor. Towards its northern ex- tremity is au elevated spot, about three acres in extent. which was formerly insulated, and was known as St. Columkille’s lsland.
